cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.AI, cs.CYBER, cs.MA 

This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) because it focuses on studying how societal opinion change emerges from individual behavior and the role of social networks in this process. It could also belong to cs.SOC (Computational Social Science) because it uses computational experiments to study social phenomena. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) because it uses agent-based models to simulate human behavior. It could also be classified under cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy) because the study of opinion change has implications for online security and privacy. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.MA (Multiagent Systems) because it uses multiple agents to simulate social behavior.
